November 17, 1997<br>
Vietnam Eases Exit Visa Rules<br>
By The Associated Press<br>
HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- Vietnam has eliminated the need for its citizens to obtain exit visas from the communist government to travel abroad, a slight easing of its foreign travel restrictions. <br><br>
Premier Phan Van Khai has signed legislation on the new policy, state-run media reported Monday. <br><br>
In the past, Vietnam issued passports valid only for specified trips and then also required travelers to obtain an exit visa to be stamped by immigration officers upon leaving the country. <br><br>
This new decree also hints at easing restrictions on hard-to-get passports. <br><br>
The premier's decree ``provides that all citizens regardless of purpose and country of destination will be granted passports under current regulations after fulfilling needed formalities.'' <br><br>
Getting a passport in Vietnam is a lengthy and arduous task involving interviews with Interior Ministry police and background checks. <br><br>
After South and North Vietnam were unified as one country under communist rule in 1975, travel restrictions were imposed on most people. Only senior Communist Party officials were permitted to travel abroad through much of the 1980s. <br><br>
In recent years, a growing number of business people, students and tourists have been traveling outside of Vietnam. <br><br>
Last year, however, Vietnam halted package tours to Hong Kong because too many Vietnamese weren't coming home. <br><br>
The United States has been pushing Vietnam to relax emigration procedures so that Hanoi can obtain a waiver to legislation that restricts U.S. trade with communist countries. <br><br>

